WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.050 --> 00:00:06.100
&gt;&gt;Hi everyone, and thanks again for coming
to another Authors@Google

00:00:06.100 --> 00:00:09.870
event from the San Francisco office.
Today we're very pleased to welcome Stephen

00:00:09.870 --> 00:00:12.260
Elliot to San Francisco.
Stephen's a novelist.

00:00:12.260 --> 00:00:15.700
He's written seven books, one of which includes
his most recent book,

00:00:15.700 --> 00:00:18.519
"The Adderall Diaries," which he'll be talking
about today.

00:00:18.519 --> 00:00:23.310
His novel "Happy Baby" was the finalist for
the New York Public Library's Young Lion Award,

00:00:23.310 --> 00:00:29.600
as well as Best Book of the Year in Salon.com,
Newsday, Chicago Newcity, the Journal News,

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:33.739
and the Village Voice.
Stephen's writing has been featured in Esquire,

00:00:33.739 --> 00:00:38.850
the New York Times, the
Believer, GQ, Best American Non-Required Reading

00:00:38.850 --> 00:00:43.030
for 2005 and 2007.
Best American Erotica and the Best Sex Writing

00:00:43.030 --> 00:00:46.640
in 2006.
He is -- he was a Wallace Stegner Fellow at

00:00:46.640 --> 00:00:50.739
Stanford University, and is
a member of the San Francisco Writers' Grotto.

00:00:50.739 --> 00:00:54.080
And he's also the editor of the Rumpus.
Please welcome Stephen Elliot.

00:00:54.080 --> 00:00:59.649
STEPHEN ELLIOTT: I wonder -- I wonder if it's
possible to convince

00:00:59.649 --> 00:01:05.480
people to move up a little bit.
And, like, sit over here, maybe.

00:01:05.480 --> 00:01:13.530
So we can have a little more of a conversation
going on.

00:01:13.530 --> 00:01:20.750
[PAUSE]
I thought -- so I'll talk a little bit about

00:01:20.750 --> 00:01:26.880
my book "The Adderall
Diaries," which you all get for free.

00:01:26.880 --> 00:01:30.790
Which I think is just -- it takes so much
pressure off of me.

00:01:30.790 --> 00:01:37.900
I've been on this crazy book tour.
I've been in 33 cities, and I did this thing.

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:41.490
You guys can copy this if you want for your
marketing strategy.

00:01:41.490 --> 00:01:45.570
I let anybody that wanted to read a copy of
the book get an advanced

00:01:45.570 --> 00:01:49.000
copy for free.
They just had to forward it within a week

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.410
to the next reader.
So 400 people signed up for that.

00:01:52.410 --> 00:01:57.900
The early reviews are really strong, and I
was encouraged to do a

00:01:57.900 --> 00:02:01.760
bigger book tour.
And -- but I didn't want to, really.

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:04.862
I mean, because it's my 7th book.
And I know what it's like to show up in a

00:02:04.862 --> 00:02:09.970
small town, and do a reading
in the nice local bookstore to ten people,

00:02:09.970 --> 00:02:12.420
and then sleep in a crappy
hotel.

00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:17.740
And it's just very lonely.
And it can be soul crushing even.

00:02:17.740 --> 00:02:21.780
So instead I sent a note to those 400 people,
and I said I would do a

00:02:21.780 --> 00:02:24.610
reading in their home.
Anybody who wanted me to do a reading in their

00:02:24.610 --> 00:02:27.930
home, I would come, and
I would sleep on their couch.

00:02:27.930 --> 00:02:32.610
And I would read to their friends.
And they would have to promise to get 20 people.

00:02:32.610 --> 00:02:37.319
And so that's what I've been doing.
I've been crossing the country reading to

00:02:37.319 --> 00:02:40.250
groups of 20 people,
generally none of whom have heard of me.

00:02:40.250 --> 00:02:43.700
Because it's like the person that's invited
me to their home has heard of me and read

00:02:43.700 --> 00:02:45.600
the book --
It's not somebody I know but it's somebody

00:02:45.600 --> 00:02:48.511
that read the book.
And I'm just reading to their friends.

00:02:48.511 --> 00:02:53.080
Their friends are just coming to a party at
the house, and they tend

00:02:53.080 --> 00:02:55.300
to stay until one in the morning -- cause
nobody leaves a reading in a

00:02:55.300 --> 00:02:57.670
home.
It's a party, kind of.

00:02:57.670 --> 00:03:01.271
And I think, I'll never have stage fright
again, you know?

00:03:01.271 --> 00:03:05.830
Cause I'm selling books like Tupperware to
people I've never met.

00:03:05.830 --> 00:03:08.420
And I'm stuck there.
I can't leave.

00:03:08.420 --> 00:03:13.500
I got to sleep on their couch.
And so, to read to a audience of people that

00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:16.050
already has the book.
And I don't have to sell you the book.

00:03:16.050 --> 00:03:19.100
Well, I'd like to convince you to read it,
and maybe get an extra copy

00:03:19.100 --> 00:03:25.700
to give as a Christmas present.
But I feel like the pressure is kind of off.

00:03:25.700 --> 00:03:30.820
So this is a story that in a way, there is
actually an intersection

00:03:30.820 --> 00:03:38.080
with Google in a way.
Because, the book -- I'll give a brief description.

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:45.590
I had had, like, writer's block for a year
and a half, two years.

00:03:45.590 --> 00:03:48.420
And I've always written.
I've written since I was like 10-years old.

00:03:48.420 --> 00:03:51.480
And I would write to communicate.
I used to write poems.

00:03:51.480 --> 00:03:55.180
When I was literally 11-years old, I had poems
wallpapering my room.

00:03:55.180 --> 00:03:58.690
I was in this, you know -- my mother was dying.
It was a very abusive home.

00:03:58.690 --> 00:04:01.790
And then, eventually the State took custody
of me.

00:04:01.790 --> 00:04:05.160
And I was in group homes, and I would just
write poems and stories all

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:08.010
the time.
And I've always written to communicate.

00:04:08.010 --> 00:04:12.790
And then I got this really bad case of writer's
block which I think was

00:04:12.790 --> 00:04:16.410
partly, was in part because I had started
making a living as a writer.

00:04:16.410 --> 00:04:20.039
Which was -- and so now those expectations.
And I don't know how to do that.

00:04:20.039 --> 00:04:24.620
It wasn't something I had ever set out to
do.

00:04:24.620 --> 00:04:30.249
So I just started, after a year, two years,
I went back on Adderall

00:04:30.249 --> 00:04:33.949
which I had taken when I was younger.
You guys know what Adderall is?

00:04:33.949 --> 00:04:36.130
It's like ritalin.
It's an ADD medication.

00:04:36.130 --> 00:04:40.229
It's basically pure amphetamine but we prescribe
it to young children.

00:04:40.229 --> 00:04:44.700
And I just started documenting going back
on Adderall.

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:53.639
Right about that time, Sean Sturgeon confessed
to eight and a half

00:04:53.639 --> 00:04:57.419
murders.
How many people here know who Sean Sturgeon

00:04:57.419 --> 00:05:01.480
is?
See, you don't know who he is because there

00:05:01.480 --> 00:05:06.210
was a gag order.
I'm going to tell you, Sean Sturgeon is best

00:05:06.210 --> 00:05:11.839
friends with Hans Reiser,
who was on trial for murdering his wife Nina

00:05:11.839 --> 00:05:19.059
Reiser.
Hans Reiser created a file system for Linux,

00:05:19.059 --> 00:05:24.719
which he, in fact, came to
Google and did one of these presentations

00:05:24.719 --> 00:05:32.439
about his file system.
And so that's the intersection with Google

00:05:32.439 --> 00:05:36.250
and the file system.
Have you heard of the Hans Reiser trial?

00:05:36.250 --> 00:05:41.229
That was a giant trial, right?
Wired blogged it.

00:05:41.229 --> 00:05:48.819
So Nina left Hans for Sean.
And they couldn't find the body.

00:05:48.819 --> 00:05:55.379
And Sean confessed to eight and a half murders.
And so, so you would think that he would be

00:05:55.379 --> 00:05:56.629
a suspect.
And, of course, he was.

00:05:56.629 --> 00:06:02.849
He was investigated pretty extensively.
And there was a gag order on that so that

00:06:02.849 --> 00:06:04.190
the Chronicle couldn't write
about it.

00:06:04.190 --> 00:06:09.819
One second.
And then, Sean and I had -- our lives had

00:06:09.819 --> 00:06:15.779
overlapped quite a bit.
We knew a lot of people in common.

00:06:15.779 --> 00:06:21.569
And in 1999, I'd done a bondage photo shoot
in his apartment which he

00:06:21.569 --> 00:06:27.689
had rented out to professional dominatrices
as dungeon space.

00:06:27.689 --> 00:06:33.069
And I won't even go into all the details.
But, our lives, we had, you know, really overlapped

00:06:33.069 --> 00:06:36.009
quite a bit.
And so I started looking into that.

00:06:36.009 --> 00:06:42.539
And that led me to the Hans Reiser trial.
And that's the book, kind of.

00:06:42.539 --> 00:06:47.159
But there's quite a bit more, actually.
Turns out in 200 pages you can fit a lot.

00:06:47.159 --> 00:06:48.159
You have a question?

00:06:48.159 --> 00:06:50.599
&gt;&gt; I was wondering what's a half a murder?

00:06:50.599 --> 00:06:54.669
STEPHEN ELLIOTT: Half a murder?
Well, originally, I thought he didn't know

00:06:54.669 --> 00:07:00.319
if the person was dead.
But when I actually got the confessions -- when

00:07:00.319 --> 00:07:05.229
I got the entire
investigation into Sean Sturgeon, it turns

00:07:05.229 --> 00:07:11.129
out the half murder is --
was that he didn't know if she was dead when

00:07:11.129 --> 00:07:13.460
he found her or if he
killed her.

00:07:13.460 --> 00:07:17.229
So it's the first murder, when he was very
young.

00:07:17.229 --> 00:07:22.210
So, that's -- so Sean Sturgeon was kind of
the untold story.

00:07:22.210 --> 00:07:26.379
Ultimately this book, though, you know, it's
not about Sean Sturgeon.

00:07:26.379 --> 00:07:33.869
And it's not really about Hans Reiser, either.
It's really there is a full, the full Hans

00:07:33.869 --> 00:07:37.990
Reiser story is in this book
and there is a full true crime book within

00:07:37.990 --> 00:07:40.719
The Adderall Diaries.
But really it's a memoir.

00:07:40.719 --> 00:07:46.189
And more specifically it's really a book about
writing and being a writer.

00:07:46.189 --> 00:07:52.129
And the file system turns out to be a really
potent metaphor.

00:07:52.129 --> 00:07:56.789
Because the file system is really the most
human part of the computer.

00:07:56.789 --> 00:08:00.870
It's the identity of the computer.
Cause it's how the computer organizes its

00:08:00.870 --> 00:08:03.789
memories.
And that's who we are.

00:08:03.789 --> 00:08:08.569
You know, we're a series of memories and interpretations
of those

00:08:08.569 --> 00:08:14.080
memories.
So I thought I'll read just -- I'll read kind

00:08:14.080 --> 00:08:18.719
of that part, maybe,
where I first find out about Sean's confession.

00:08:18.719 --> 00:08:21.889
And I'm going to read, I'll read one short
section.

00:08:21.889 --> 00:08:25.619
Then we could do some Q&amp;A if you guys have
any questions.

00:08:25.619 --> 00:08:30.009
And then I'll read another section and then
we can do a little more

00:08:30.009 --> 00:08:36.419
Q&amp;A.
So this section should take about eight minutes.

00:08:36.419 --> 00:08:40.800
The morning the after the fight, I get a call
from Josh, a staff writer

00:08:40.800 --> 00:08:45.160
at Wired magazine.
He's working on a profile of Hans Reiser,

00:08:45.160 --> 00:08:48.380
a brilliant computer
programmer accused of killing his estranged

00:08:48.380 --> 00:08:52.410
wife.
I helped Josh track down Hans' former best

00:08:52.410 --> 00:08:58.250
friend, Sean Sturgeon.
Sean and I have several girlfriends in common,

00:08:58.250 --> 00:09:01.440
and I once did a bondage
photo shoot in his apartment when he wasn't

00:09:01.440 --> 00:09:03.720
home.
When I say girlfriends, I don't mean that

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:07.970
we were engaged with the same
women just that we knew, we had girls who

00:09:07.970 --> 00:09:11.649
were friends.
Legally, since this is being videotaped I

00:09:11.649 --> 00:09:17.899
should be clear about this.
I don't remember ever meeting him.

00:09:17.899 --> 00:09:23.380
But our paths have crossed so many times it
almost doesn't make sense.

00:09:23.380 --> 00:09:26.970
Josh's calling to say he found out something
incredible about the case.

00:09:26.970 --> 00:09:35.139
Your guy Sean just confessed to eight murders,
maybe nine.

00:09:35.139 --> 00:09:40.240
Why maybe nine?
He isn't sure if one of the victims is dead.

00:09:40.240 --> 00:09:44.100
Josh says Sean's not under arrest and he's
refusing to tell the

00:09:44.100 --> 00:09:48.160
district attorney the names of the people
he killed.

00:09:48.160 --> 00:09:51.360
Sean told Josh that he confessed to D.A. because
he's a born again

00:09:51.360 --> 00:09:55.170
Christian and thought the jury would want
to know.

00:09:55.170 --> 00:09:59.980
It seemed the right thing to do or rather,
he posited the question --

00:09:59.980 --> 00:10:05.529
don't you think the jury would want to know?
But then he said Hans knew about his murders

00:10:05.529 --> 00:10:07.800
and he was confessing in
order to beat Hans to the punch.

00:10:07.800 --> 00:10:13.100
Maybe he confessed for both reasons.
Or maybe he confessed for reasons that had

00:10:13.100 --> 00:10:16.190
nothing to do with Reiser or
the jury.

00:10:16.190 --> 00:10:19.790
He denied having anything to do with Hans'
wife disappearance.

00:10:19.790 --> 00:10:26.290
He told Josh give me some Sodium Pentothal
or any truth serum, put a

00:10:26.290 --> 00:10:30.110
little bit of Ecstasy in there and ask me
if I've killed Nina.

00:10:30.110 --> 00:10:35.450
I have never been a threat to her.
Josh told the police and the district attorney

00:10:35.450 --> 00:10:39.120
that his victims had
physically and sexually abused him and his

00:10:39.120 --> 00:10:42.920
sister in the East Bay
commune where they were raised.

00:10:42.920 --> 00:10:49.139
He claimed he hadn't killed anyone since 1996.
The commune interested me.

00:10:49.139 --> 00:10:53.330
I know the places where adults come in conflict,
or -- I know the

00:10:53.330 --> 00:10:56.730
places where the adults come in contact with
unsupervised children.

00:10:56.730 --> 00:11:00.680
Between 14 and 18, I was in five different
state-funded childcare

00:11:00.680 --> 00:11:04.529
facilities including three group homes, a
mental hospital, and a

00:11:04.529 --> 00:11:08.300
temporary youth shelter that stuffed 30 children
into each room.

00:11:08.300 --> 00:11:13.040
In those places, you can never tell who to
trust.

00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:15.850
When I'm done talking to Josh, I feel like
I'm waiting for something.

00:11:15.850 --> 00:11:20.690
The group homes were a long time ago.
It's still morning, and I put a pot of water

00:11:20.690 --> 00:11:25.009
on the stove.
I call Josh back and ask him for Sean's phone

00:11:25.009 --> 00:11:28.440
number.
If Sean committed eight murders, it's a huge

00:11:28.440 --> 00:11:32.639
story.
I think, here is a man willing to wait eight

00:11:32.639 --> 00:11:37.650
years, willing to wait
years, to get revenge on the people who stole

00:11:37.650 --> 00:11:42.100
his childhood.
I think of In Cold Blood and the Executioner's

00:11:42.100 --> 00:11:45.949
Song.
Two of my favorite books, both set around

00:11:45.949 --> 00:11:48.410
spectacular murders and
written by novelists.

00:11:48.410 --> 00:11:53.230
I know people who have known Sean for more
than a decade.

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:56.689
I have the inside track, and there's something
else about the case.

00:11:56.689 --> 00:12:01.970
Nina Reiser's body was never found.
But I'm getting ahead of myself.

00:12:01.970 --> 00:12:06.139
I don't know if Sean will talk to me.
If he did kill eight people, surely the police

00:12:06.139 --> 00:12:08.589
would have arrested him
by now.

00:12:08.589 --> 00:12:12.899
And why isn't he a suspect in the disappearance
of Nina Reiser?

00:12:12.899 --> 00:12:17.339
After calling Sean and leaving a message I
bicycled through the city

00:12:17.339 --> 00:12:22.490
down Market, toward the Castro, my right pant
leg rolled up so as not

00:12:22.490 --> 00:12:28.079
to get caught in the chain.
My bicycle is my prize possession, an old

00:12:28.079 --> 00:12:33.329
Peugeot I picked up for $150 nine years ago.
I live a spare existence.

00:12:33.329 --> 00:12:36.290
I haven't owned a car since I first got to
this city.

00:12:36.290 --> 00:12:39.420
I cut right past the Gay and Lesbian Center,
the Three Dollar Bill

00:12:39.420 --> 00:12:41.420
Cafe.
Something is tugging on me.

00:12:41.420 --> 00:12:46.709
I had heard of Nina's murder.
But never the full story.

00:12:46.709 --> 00:12:50.600
I'd heard about Sean and how Nina's disappearance
crushed him.

00:12:50.600 --> 00:12:56.170
He took to bed, paralyzed with grief.
He was in love with his best friend's wife.

00:12:56.170 --> 00:12:59.920
It was all just passing information.
But eight murders?

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:03.990
Revenge killings?
Eight murders isn't revenge.

00:13:03.990 --> 00:13:10.069
Eight murders is a serial killer.
I go to the park to meet a girl I know.

00:13:10.069 --> 00:13:13.769
Someone who has taken a habit of coming to
my readings.

00:13:13.769 --> 00:13:17.600
She's engaged and lives with her fiance between
the Marina and Russian

00:13:17.600 --> 00:13:21.320
Hill.
I've only seen her once before and she explained

00:13:21.320 --> 00:13:23.939
their relationship.
It was simple.

00:13:23.939 --> 00:13:30.850
He was monogamous and believed in monogamy.
She cheated on him and always would.

00:13:30.850 --> 00:13:34.939
She arrives --
It's very San Francisco, I think.

00:13:34.939 --> 00:13:39.569
She arrives wearing a black dress and sandals.
Her skin is so pale all I can think of is

00:13:39.569 --> 00:13:42.999
milk.
I don't think of my complicity in her unfaithfulness.

00:13:42.999 --> 00:13:45.199
I don't want to.
I don't love her.

00:13:45.199 --> 00:13:49.490
She's just someone I know.
I wait as she walks across the grass in her

00:13:49.490 --> 00:13:53.319
sandals.
A man stops her and asks if she is willing

00:13:53.319 --> 00:13:54.879
to be in one of his
paintings.

00:13:54.879 --> 00:14:00.050
She talks with him for a moment.
Her head turned his way, her body pointing

00:14:00.050 --> 00:14:03.399
toward me.
He doesn't have any paint.

00:14:03.399 --> 00:14:07.019
He wears dark, heavy clothes, his belongings
bound in garbage bags

00:14:07.019 --> 00:14:10.550
around him.
The sun is brilliant and the colorful houses

00:14:10.550 --> 00:14:12.819
are brightly lit along the
hills.

00:14:12.819 --> 00:14:17.040
On some days, the fog catches on their drainpipes
like cotton, but

00:14:17.040 --> 00:14:22.529
today it's easy to see why people want to
live here.

00:14:22.529 --> 00:14:26.949
Easy to see San Francisco for the gentle paradise
it is.

00:14:26.949 --> 00:14:32.649
We lie in the grass with my shirt pulled up.
I forget all about the De La Hoya's fight

00:14:32.649 --> 00:14:34.089
and Sean Sturgeon's
confession.

00:14:34.089 --> 00:14:37.480
I ask her to pinch my nipple and she does.
But it isn't enough.

00:14:37.480 --> 00:14:40.810
I asked her to do it harder and soon there
is blood everywhere.

00:14:40.810 --> 00:14:44.610
There are people nearby but they don't seem
to notice.

00:14:44.610 --> 00:14:48.170
For most of it, she keeps her hand over my
mouth and I close my eyes

00:14:48.170 --> 00:14:52.180
and drift away.
It's okay, she says.

00:14:52.180 --> 00:14:56.629
That's only half the day.
There's a barbecue and then a reading.

00:14:56.629 --> 00:14:58.480
And then a party.
There's always a party.

00:14:58.480 --> 00:15:03.120
I dance with a girl.
How do you know Eric, I ask between songs.

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:07.160
I don't, she says, my boyfriend knows him.
I dance better after that.

00:15:07.160 --> 00:15:09.780
It's still a weekend, after all.
It's still San Francisco.

00:15:09.780 --> 00:15:11.999
Everything is beautiful.
Really, it seems perfect.

00:15:11.999 --> 00:15:16.249
The DJ looks like Napoleon Dynamite and spins
pop songs from the 80s on

00:15:16.249 --> 00:15:18.680
vinyl.
I'm 35 years old.

00:15:18.680 --> 00:15:22.269
The woman I'm dancing with has curly black
hair and moves with steady

00:15:22.269 --> 00:15:25.499
grace, her silk dress rolling in waves down
her arms.

00:15:25.499 --> 00:15:29.600
I feel loose and fine.
I take five dollars from another writer who

00:15:29.600 --> 00:15:32.720
put his money inexplicably
on De La Hoya.

00:15:32.720 --> 00:15:37.050
Always bet on youth, I tell him.
It's one in the morning.

00:15:37.050 --> 00:15:39.329
I don't imagine anything can ever go wrong.

00:15:39.329 --> 00:15:43.129
So that's -- that's that section.
[APPLAUSE]

00:15:43.129 --> 00:15:52.050
I keep a little timepiece over here so I know
where we're at.

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:54.310
Questions on anything?

